{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568496"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:16:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:16:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20969"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20969","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20969"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.67,0.09,0.17,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13844"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98146"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13844","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13844"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20969"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80646"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"1911"},{"type":"tags","id":"2649"},{"type":"tags","id":"3505"},{"type":"tags","id":"4969"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33451"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33645"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43735"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98146","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98146"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 58-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic for review of her chronic conditions. She was diagnosed with type 2 diabetes mellitus 10 years ago and hypertension 5 years ago. Her medical history includes obesity and dyslipidaemia. Her current medications include metformin 1000 mg twice daily, perindopril 5 mg daily, and atorvastatin 20 mg daily. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. Her body mass index is 32 kg/m\u00b2.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal: HbA1c 7.8% (62 mmol/mol), estimated glomerular filtration rate 48 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2 (\u0026gt;90), urine albumin-to-creatinine ratio 45 mg/mmol (\u0026lt;3.5), total cholesterol 4.2 mmol/L (3.9-5.5), and potassium 4.6 mmol/L (3.5-5.0).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following medications would provide the most benefit for slowing progression of her kidney disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Add finerenone","Add empagliflozin","Add semaglutide","Increase perindopril dose","Add spironolactone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has type 2 diabetes with evidence of diabetic kidney disease (reduced estimated glomerular filtration rate and significant albuminuria). The question asks about the most beneficial medication to slow progression of kidney disease in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd empagliflozin\u003C/strong\u003E (an SGLT2 inhibitor) is the most appropriate option. Multiple trials (EMPA-REG OUTCOME, CREDENCE, DAPA-CKD) show SGLT2 inhibitors significantly reduce kidney disease progression in patients with type 2 diabetes and albuminuria. These trials all showed substantial renal benefits, including reduced risk of progression to end-stage kidney disease, doubling of serum creatinine, and renal death. These benefits appear to be independent of glycaemic control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECurrent guidelines recommend SGLT2 inhibitors as a preferred add-on therapy for patients with type 2 diabetes and chronic kidney disease, particularly those with albuminuria. SGLT2 inhibitors are also now recommended for people with chronic kidney disease and proteinuria, with or without diabetes, to reduce the risk of progressive decline in kidney function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease perindopril dose\u003C/strong\u003E may provide some additional benefit for blood pressure control and possibly reduce albuminuria further. ACE inhibitors like perindopril are indeed first-line agents for patients with diabetic kidney disease and albuminuria. However, the patient is already on an ACE inhibitor, and adding an SGLT2 inhibitor would likely provide greater additional benefit for kidney protection than optimising ACE inhibitor dosing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd semaglutide\u003C/strong\u003E, a GLP-1 receptor agonist, has demonstrated cardiovascular benefits and modest renal benefits in patients with type 2 diabetes. However, the renoprotective effects of GLP-1 receptor agonists are generally considered less robust than those of SGLT2 inhibitors. While semaglutide would be beneficial for glycaemic control and weight management, it would not be the first choice specifically for kidney protection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn the FIDELIO-DKD trial, \u003Cstrong\u003Eadding finerenone\u003C/strong\u003E, a non-steroidal mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist, reduced the risk of worsening kidney disease in patients with type 2 diabetes and chronic kidney disease. While this is an evidence-based option, current guidelines recommend SGLT2 inhibitors before considering finerenone. Finerenone would be a reasonable addition after optimising RAAS blockade and adding an SGLT2 inhibitor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdd spironolactone\u003C/strong\u003E, a steroidal mineralocorticoid receptor antagonist, can reduce albuminuria but has not been shown to have the same degree of kidney protection as SGLT2 inhibitors in patients with diabetic kidney disease. Additionally, adding spironolactone to an ACE inhibitor increases the risk of hyperkalaemia, particularly in a patient with already reduced kidney function (an eGFR of 48 mL/min/1.73m\u00b2).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["SGLT2 inhibitors reduce the risk of progression of chronic kidney disease in patients with type 2 diabetes and albuminuria.","SGLT2 inhibitors are recommended for people with chronic kidney disease and proteinuria, with or without diabetes, to reduce the risk of progressive decline in kidney function.","ACE inhibitors and ARBs are first-line agents for patients with diabetic kidney disease and albuminuria.","Non-steroidal mineralocorticoid receptor antagonists like finerenone provide additional renal protection in diabetic kidney disease with albuminuria.","GLP-1 receptor agonists have cardiovascular benefits but more modest renal protective effects compared to SGLT2 inhibitors."],"references":["Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) Management in Primary Care (5th edition). Kidney Health Australia, Melbourne, 2024. Available from: https://assets.kidney.org.au/resources/KHA-CKD-Handbook-5th-Ed-July2024.pdf","Brendon L Neuen, Emily K Yeung, Janani Rangaswami, Muthiah Vaduganathan, Combination therapy as a new standard of care in diabetic and non-diabetic chronic kidney disease, Nephrology Dialysis Transplantation, Volume 40, Issue Supplement_1, January 2025, Pages i59\u2013i69, https://doi.org/10.1093/ndt/gfae258"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80646"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20969"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80646","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80646"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-11T22:33:44+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-11T22:34:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items